IT Budget




Credit Suisse (USA) is part of global financial services company Credit Suisse Group based in Switzerland. The company offers securities, underwriting and trading, merger and acquisition consulting services, financial research and analysis, private equity investment, and derivative and risk management… MoreCredit Suisse (USA) is part of global financial services company Credit Suisse Group based in Switzerland. The company offers securities, underwriting and trading, merger and acquisition consulting services, financial research and analysis, private equity investment, and derivative and risk management products. Credit Suisse also provides asset management and financial advisory services to individuals and corporate investors.
IT Priorities:
•Maintaining cost efficiency is an important priority for Credit Suisse Group AG.
•Infrastructure needs have been a constant challenge; company strategy includes implementing infrastructure upgrades every 18 months to 2 years.
•The current focus is network and storage solutions.
•Virtualization projects were initially implemented… MoreIT Priorities:
•Maintaining cost efficiency is an important priority for Credit Suisse Group AG.
•Infrastructure needs have been a constant challenge; company strategy includes implementing infrastructure upgrades every 18 months to 2 years.
•The current focus is network and storage solutions.
•Virtualization projects were initially implemented as a result of data center capacity challenges; this is a current pain point, and the company will be investing in data centers in the future.
•Data Privacy is a major priority, and the company will be looking into security projects in the future.
•Harmonization and simplification of the IT applications environment, without jeopardizing mobility or flexibility, is a constant goal.
•Up to 90% of new services being implemented are virtualized.

IT Structure
The Technology Infrastructure Services (TIS) Group division manages global IT and infrastructure services for the company.
•IT operations are overseen by CFO David Mathers, based in Zurich; Three CIOs report to him, including Claude Honegger, also located in Zürich. 
•The CIOs for Front Office Applications and Global Infrastructure are based in the USA.
•The company maintains five centers of excellence globally supporting various business operations, including IT.
•The Architecture group handles the selection and deployment of the systems and applications across the organization, taking part in project planning and monitoring.
•IT for Credit Suisse North America is profiled separately.

IT Intelligence Snippets

2013
•Data Privacy is a major priority, and the company will be looking into security projects in the future.
•Virtualization projects were initially implemented as a result of data center capacity challenges; this is a current pain point, and the company will be investing in data centers in the future 
•The IT department has been looking into cloud solutions, and is maintaining some private cloud infrastructure.
•The company currently uses software as a service (Saas) for some human resources and accounting applications, but are not looking into additional public cloud solutions.
•Approximately 62% of current infrastructure is virtualized, and up to 90% of new services being implemented are virtualized.
•As of May, the IT department is focusing on developing and expanding eCommerce solutions, especially mobile solutions and eTrading.
•In April, the company announced a continued strategy of savings through utilization and development of shared infrastructure and support services across the Group. 
•The current consolidation efforts will be focused on the company's two operating divisions.
•In fiscal year 2013, the IT department is looking to achieve significant spending cuts, approximately 30 percent. Outsourcing opportunities has also been an interest.

2012
•The IT environment consists of more than 7,000 applications, a majority of them developed in-house.
•In late 2012, Credit Suisse put a project to upgrade its Oracle E-Business product suite within Switzerland on hold, and is retaining legacy mainframe systems. 
•Financial difficulties of the bank forced this decision.
•Global IT spending is nearly $3.5 billion per year.
•The company employs approximately 15,000 IT specialists globally both internally and externally, including nearly 6,000 in Switzerland.





